channel.title: Latest News and News Headlines | Daily Telegraph

item.title: Iran looks east after China-led bloc OKs entry
item.description: Iran on Saturday hailed its acceptance into a China and Russia-led bloc, an eastward turn it sees as opening access to major world markets and a counter to crippling Western sanctions.

item.title: Inter crash six past Bologna to move top of Serie A
item.description: Inter Milan bounced back from midweek Champions League disappointment on Saturday with a 6-1 hammering of Bologna which moved the reigning champions top of Serie A. Simone Inzaghi's side were sucker-punched in the last minute by Real Madrid in Wednesday's single-goal defeat but made no mistake this time at the San Siro.

item.title: Mane reaches century as Liverpool top Premier League, Arsenal ease Arteta pressure
item.description: Sadio Mane reached 100 career goals for Liverpool in a 3-0 win against Crystal Palace that sent the Reds top of the Premier League, while Arsenal eased the pressure on Mikel Arteta with a battling 1-0 victory at Burnley on Saturday.

item.title: Sparse attendance at rally in support of US Capitol rioters
item.description: A few hundred protesters turned up Saturday in Washington to rally in support of the pro-Trump rioters who ransacked the US Capitol on January 6, but they were outnumbered by a robust security presence and journalists.

item.title: Hong Kong elite selects powerful new ‘patriots only’ committee
item.description: Hong Kong's political elite will select a powerful committee on Sunday which will choose the city's next leader and nearly half the legislature under a new "patriots only" system imposed by Beijing.

item.title: Bold new Covid-19 test in development
item.description: A finger prick test that does not detect a Covid-19 infection but rather a person’s immunity to the virus is being developed and partly funded by the Victorian government.

item.title: ‘Attack’ hits Hungary primary polls aimed to challenge Orban: opposition
item.description: Hungary's first-ever primary elections to find a candidate to challenge right-wing Prime Minister Viktor Orban got off to a rocky start on Saturday with voting suspended due to what organisers said was a suspected cyber attack.

item.title: ‘We were honest’: French sub snub defended
item.description: Defence Minister Peter Dutton has rebuked accusations Australia lied to its French counterparts as the fall out over a decision to tear up a contract for submarines continues.

item.title: Vax targets not ‘freedom day’, doctors say
item.description: Australians are being cautioned by the nation’s peak medical body to not view the achievement of key vaccination milestones as “freedom day”.
